{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522115"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13800"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13800"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.82,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6417"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 48 hour history of constant and severe epigastric pain, which radiates to his back and is associated with nausea and vomiting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks about four cans of beer a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended and tender to palpation in the epigastrium (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appendicitis","Perforated peptic ulcer","Acute pancreatitis","Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm","Mesenteric ischaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and the presence of Cullen\u0027s sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esevere acute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s history of heavy alcohol consumption is a significant risk factor. The severe abdominal pain radiating to the back is characteristic of acute pancreatitis. Cullen\u0027s sign, while not pathognomonic, is associated with severe pancreatitis and indicates the presence of retroperitoneal haemorrhage, suggesting a poor prognosis. Cullen\u0027s sign describes the presence of blood around the umbilicus, which has tracked there from (usually) a retroperitoneal source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute appendicitis \u003C/strong\u003Eshould always be considered in any case of acute abdominal pain. However the clinical presentation of constant epigastric pain described here would not really fit for such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforated peptic ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden, severe abdominal pain and signs of peritonitis. While it can cause significant morbidity, it would not typically cause Cullen\u0027s sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E can cause retroperitoneal hemorrhage and potentially lead to Cullen\u0027s sign. However, it typically occurs in older individuals and presents with severe, tearing back pain and signs of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe abdominal pain out of proportion to physical findings. While it can be life-threatening, it would not cause Cullen\u0027s sign.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cullen\u0027s sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) is associated with severe acute pancreatitis and retroperitoneal haemorrhage.","The presence of Cullen\u0027s sign in acute pancreatitis indicates a poor prognosis and may necessitate intensive care management."],"references":["Ganguly D, Chandra A. Cullen sign and Grey Turner sign in acute pancreatitis. The American Journal of Medicine. 2022;135(2):E427-438. Available at: https://www.amjmed.com/article/S0002-9343(22)00579-4/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13800"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20743"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20743"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O8VySEC7wmge2DLZtNQlBd4k4B1ddB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O8VySEC7wmge2DLZtNQlBd4k4B1ddB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T15:29:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T15:29:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6417"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id"